770
01:08:56,322 --> 01:09:02,084
So as you know, No Child Left Behind has been replaced by Every Student Succeeds Act.

771
01:09:04,505 --> 01:09:09,727
And that legislation begins in 2016-2017 as a transition year, with full implementation in 2017-2018.

772
01:09:16,684 --> 01:09:18,624
Now, there are several key elements of the Act.

773
01:09:19,345 --> 01:09:30,647
I want to give you enough of it so you understand it, but not so much that you, you know, get overwhelmed by it because there's an awful lot of pieces and we'll have to break it down piece at a time in order for it to really be understood.

774
01:09:30,667 --> 01:09:38,029
ESSA comprises nine title grants which provide funding to districts and states.

775
01:09:38,769 --> 01:09:40,289
Currently, there are about five or six.

776
01:09:41,169 --> 01:09:44,010
I'm not sure how we count them these days because they keep putting them together.

777
01:09:44,737 --> 01:09:54,382
Title IV grant represents a new funding source, which is an allocation grant for districts in the area of student support services, something that would speak to some of the discussion we had a little bit earlier.

778
01:09:55,415 --> 01:10:08,904
Districts and states are required to conform to the requirements of ESSA, so that No Child Left Behind is now giving way to ESSA and districts and states now must adopt ESSA rules.

779
01:10:09,684 --> 01:10:18,249
ESSA encourages state agencies to think differently about how best to support low-performing schools as the school improvement grants are no longer available.

780
01:10:18,810 --> 01:10:20,471
So they're asking the department

781
01:10:20,907 --> 01:10:26,309
Department of Elementary and Secondary Education to talk to us about how we could best benefit from their help.

782
01:10:27,670 --> 01:10:31,931
That should be a very robust discussion, especially in our conference and so on and so forth going forward.

783
01:10:33,912 --> 01:10:38,594
ESSA minimizes Title I prescriptive school and district accountability requirements.

784
01:10:39,374 --> 01:10:48,258
No Child Left Behind had very, very specific things under Title I. ESSA wiped some of it away, but it adds some things that are interesting too.

785
01:10:49,973 --> 01:10:52,414
Equitable access is perhaps one of the biggest areas.

786
01:10:52,514 --> 01:10:53,755
What is equitable access?

787
01:10:54,155 --> 01:10:56,016
Does it mean every school gets the same thing?

788
01:10:56,717 --> 01:10:59,919
Does it mean it's based on proportion of low income?

789
01:10:59,979 --> 01:11:01,760
Is it based on proportion of high needs?

790
01:11:02,260 --> 01:11:02,640
What is it?

791
01:11:03,441 --> 01:11:05,262
Equitable doesn't automatically mean things.

792
01:11:05,302 --> 01:11:08,824
What if you have a teacher in a school who makes $80,000 a year and a teacher makes $60,000 a year?

793
01:11:11,494 --> 01:11:15,817
Is it different or is it the same thing as long as there's a teacher there who's experienced and can do the job?

794
01:11:16,377 --> 01:11:17,998
Those things are yet to be fleshed out.

795
01:11:18,579 --> 01:11:22,381
And it's problematic because naturally we hire teachers at different stages of their career.

796
01:11:23,202 --> 01:11:27,624
And a lot of it's based on, you know, how many years they've been with us and what their degrees are.

797
01:11:28,145 --> 01:11:32,007
That doesn't necessarily mean they're better or worse at what they will do.

798
01:11:32,027 --> 01:11:39,112
There's a shift in focus on the Title II program from highly qualified to reporting on student learning experience.

799
01:11:40,122 --> 01:11:45,205
Instead of determining just the teachers are highly qualified, the question will be, what have the students learned?

800
01:11:45,505 --> 01:11:48,307
They have to give us some rubrics to determine that going forward.

801
01:11:50,749 --> 01:11:56,953
It focuses mostly on quality access to education, access to quality education.

802
01:11:58,934 --> 01:12:07,079
DESE is going to continue to collect certain data, but it doesn't mean it's going to have a particular impact on what we do or don't do.

803
01:12:08,382 --> 01:12:14,466
Inexperienced teachers will be expected to do different things, but we haven't got guidelines yet.

804
01:12:16,148 --> 01:12:23,372
Total funding for this year has been about the same, a little bit different, with a larger shift in Title IV student support money.

805
01:12:24,293 --> 01:12:27,956
